post_text:
Kingsport City Schools is pleased to announce that Dobyns-Bennett High School is the recipient of the National Athletic Trainers' Association (NATA) Safe Sports School 1st Team award for its athletic program, valid through September 2023. ğŸ™ŒğŸ™ŒğŸŒŸ The award champions safety and recognizes secondary schools that have met the recommended standards to improve safety in sports. The award reinforces the importance of providing the best level of care, injury prevention, and treatment.

"Dobyns-Bennett is very lucky to have two of the best athletic trainers in high school athletics - Head Athletic Trainer, Kevin Trivette and Assistant Athletic Trainer, Briana Branson," said Dobyns-Bennett High School Athletic Director Frankie DeBusk. "This award represents their hard work, dedication, and demonstrates their continuous hours on and off the playing field in order to support our student athletes. We are humbled and honored to be selected for this award, but the attention needs to be focused on Kevin and Bree, as they provide the safest environment for our high school athletes."

post_text: ATTN: Kingsport City Schools Families. Tonight's called meeting (July 28, 2020 at 6 p.m.) will include a 30 minute public comment period (up to three [3] minutes per person) where individuals will have an opportunity to express their feedback to the Board of Education via Zoom. Please note, with all public comment periods, a dialogue will not take place, but rather the Board will hear your comments. If you are a part of the Kingsport City Schools community and would like to address the Board this evening, please email your name, street address, and email to info@k12k.com. Due to the time allowance given for public comment, only the first 10 individuals will receive a Zoom invitation to address the Board. Take note, the Board will meet in person this evening, but the meeting will be held via Zoom. Access to the KCS Administrative Support Center will be limited to Board Members and essential KCS personnel only. Thank you.

post_text: *UPDATE* The Kingsport City Schools Board of Education will hold a called meeting on Tuesday, July 28, 2020 at 6 p.m. Per Executive Order Number 51 issued by Governor Bill Lee on June 29, 2020, the called meeting will be held electronically via Zoom; which will be streamed LIVE on our Facebook Page. Members of the Board may attend the meeting electronically, including, but not limited to, telephonically. The agenda can be accessed at the following link https://go.boarddocs.com/tn/kingscs/Board.nsf/vpublic?open. The purpose of the called meeting is to consider approval of the "Kingsport City Schools Operations Manual - Framework for Opening the 2020-21 School Year," a potential revision to the 2020-21 KCS School Calendar, and to consider approval of revised Policy 2.601 - Fundraising Activities. The regularly scheduled Board Work Session has been cancelled.

post_text: â€¼ï¸ATTN: Kingsport City Schools Elementary School Families!â€¼ï¸An adjustment has been made to the elementary school schedule, moving the elementary school day to â¡ï¸8:30 a.m. - 3:30 p.m.â¬…ï¸ beginning with the 2020-21 school year. The proposed 15-minute shift is for multiple reasons. One, with middle/high school bus runs taking place prior to the elementary runs, the 15 minutes provides additional time needed for student temperature checks and bus cleaning between runs due to COVID-19 disinfecting. Regarding afternoon bus transportation, the 15 minutes will also mean elementary students will have less wait-time between the end of the instructional day and when buses arrive for student transportation home. Student drop-off will still begin at 7:30 a.m.

post_text: Yesterday evening, we sent an email to our families with information for the 2020-21 school year. As you know, Kingsport City Schools is offering students the option to attend their zoned school for Face-to-Face (F2F) in-person learning or participate in Remote Choice Learning 2020 (RCL2020), where students will access their curriculum at home via the internet. With either option, all students are expected to progress academically. Visit www.k12k.com - "KCS Remote Choice Learning 2020 Information" for details. We are developing our FAQ (thanks for the questions) and will publish that in the coming days.

post_text: Please take a moment to watch this excellent "KCS Reopening Plan Epi Curve Numbers Breakdown" tutorial created by D-B EXCEL student Zane Franklin. He's done a great job explaining and showing how KCS determines the three opening scenarios (green, yellow, red) based on the TN Department of Health's Epi Curve numbers. KCS and the Sullivan County Regional Health Department look at Sullivan County numbers based on the "average case rate of new COVID-19 cases per 100,000 Sullivan County residents over the last 14 days." Please visit www.k12k.com - KCS Reopening Plan for the TN Department of Health's Epi Curves webpage or scroll down to our July 7, 2020 Update.

post_text: Kingsport City Schools has announced that Dr. Kelli Seymour has been named principal of John Sevier Middle School, effective immediately. Dr. Seymour most recently served as principal at Theodore Roosevelt Elementary School for the last three years. Prior to coming to Roosevelt Elementary, Seymour was interim assistant principal at Robinson Middle School, where she had also served as associate principal. Seymour has previously taught with Hamblen County Schools and Johnson City Schools and was a Reward School Ambassador for the Tennessee Department of Education. â€œI am excited and honored to be part of the Warrior tribe,â€ said Dr. Seymour. â€œI look forward to working with the dedicated faculty and staff at John Sevier Middle School to provide our students with the best educational foundation to become World Changing Warriors.â€ ğŸ“¸ credit: Allen Greene Photography #principalsofinstagram #middleschool #breathelife #kingsport #thisiskingsport

post_text: The Kingsport City Schools School Nutrition Services department will again provide "Summer Meals for Kids" located at Sevier Middle School, Johnson Elementary School, and Washington Elementary School. There will also be eight school bus routes delivering meals to children around Kingsport. No cost meals will be served Monday â€“ Friday to all children 18 years of age or younger from May 26 â€“ July 17, 2020 (excluding July 3). "Grab and Go" meals will be provided from 10:30 a.m. â€“ 1:30 p.m. at school sites and via school bus delivery. No meals will be served on weekends. There are no income requirements to participate in this summer meals program. A program flyer with school bus route delivery locations and times can be found on www.k12k.com. #dowhatyoucan #weloveourstudents #breathelife #onetribe #uplifttoday #kingsport #thisiskingsport

post_text: Kingsport City Schools has announced that Dr. Corey Gardenhour has been named principal of Ross N. Robinson Middle School, effective July 1, 2020. Dr. Gardenhour most recently served as the Director of Schools for Elizabethton (TN) City Schools. Dr. Gardenhour holds a Bachelor of Science degree and a Master of Education degree from Milligan College, an Educational Specialist degree from Lincoln Memorial University, and an Educational Doctorate in Educational Leadership and Policy Analysis from East Tennessee State University. â€œI am excited to return to Kingsport City Schools where I can renew many personal and professional relationships with so many members of the community,â€ said Dr. Gardenhour. â€œI look forward to working with the teachers, staff, parents, and students at Robinson. Our team will be working hard over the summer so we can be ready to move our students forward once they return.â€ #principalsofinstagram #middleschool #newemployee #breathelife #kingspoet #thisiskingsport

post_text: ATTN Kingsport City Schools Families of Pre-K - 5th Grade students: Kingsport City Schools is committed to keeping the learning process happening while schools are closed for the rest of the 2019-20 school year. We have prepared a second round of learning packets for elementary students to keep your child engaged in learning. Learning packets will be distributed at your home school Friday, April 24th from 8 a.m. - 2 p.m. and again on Monday, April 27th from 10 a.m. - 5 p.m. Additional information regarding pick up procedures will be shared in the coming days from your school principal. Please be on the lookout for that and stay in touch with your teachers. Be well!

post_text: During this most unusual time of separation, we hope you are staying healthy and well. It is odd to not share classrooms and hallways together, but please know that everyone with Kingsport City Schools is thinking about you and missing being able to physically learn together at school. We cannot wait until we are all back together. We understand that there are many questions related to academics, grades, and school operational issues between now and the end of the school year. An FAQ has been developed to help share information that will address many of these issues, and we encourage you to review this. If you have questions that are not addressed in the FAQ, please share those with your teacher or administrator so they can be addressed. Click here to view the FAQ now: https://www.k12k.com/apps/pages/index.jsp?uREC_ID=1733076&type=d&pREC_ID=1908564 #weloveourstudents #weloveouremployees #communitymatters #bettertogether #onetribe #breathelife

post_text: By Executive Order Number 16 issued by Governor Bill Lee on March 20, 2020, the Kingsport City Schools Board of Education will hold a meeting electronically on Tuesday, April 14, 2020 at 6 p.m. Members of the Board may attend the meeting electronically, including, but not limited to, telephonically. The agenda can be accessed at the following link https://go.boarddocs.com/tn/kingscs/Board.nsf/vpublic?open. In light of COVID-19 (Coronavirus) and to help prevent its spread and in order to protect the health, safety, and welfare of the public, there will be no physical access permitted by the public at the physical location of the meeting. The meeting will be conducted electronically, and members of the public can attend and listen to the meeting electronically via www.k12k.com - Homepage - Latest News or watch live on our KCS Facebook Page (www.facebook.com/KptSchools). Alternatively, the audio archive of the meeting will be available at www.k12k.com - Board - Board Schedule & Notes within two (2) business days of the meeting.

post_text: ATTN Kingsport City Schools Families: Kingsport City Schools is committed to keeping the learning process happening while schools are closed during this time. Students in grades K-5 received learning packets before Spring Break, while students in grades 6-12 are receiving information from their teachers electronically through their 1:1 device. post_text: ATTN: Kingsport City Schools Families: As a reminder, our food distribution program will relaunch tomorrow, Monday, March 30, 2020 providing a free breakfast and lunch to any child age 18 or under. Just like before break, that distribution will take place at our schools and also on all our regular bus routes. Please be aware of one change, both breakfast and lunch will now be given out at one time, between 10 a.m. and 2 p.m. Hopefully, that will make it more efficient and require only one trip for everyone. If youâ€™re not on a bus route and need a food delivery, please call (423) 392.4670 to help us coordinate that. Please be aware that we have added some additional safety procedures in how we are handing out food, trying to keep everyone as safe as possible.

The agenda can be accessed at the following link - https://go.boarddocs.com/tn/kingscs/Board.nsf/vpublic?open. The regularly scheduled Board Work Session has been cancelled. The meeting will be conducted electronically, and members of the public can attend and listen to the meeting electronically via www.k12k.com - Homepage - Latest News or watch live on our KCS Facebook Page (www.facebook.com/KptSchools). Alternatively, the audio archive of the meeting will be available at www.k12k.com - Board - Board Schedule & Notes within two (2) business days of the meeting.

post_text: ATTN: Families and Staff of Bristol, Kingsport City Schools, and Sullivan County Schools: We have continued to consult with the Sullivan County Health Department, the Tennessee Department of Health, and the CDC since our last communication, receiving updates and information related to COVID-19 (Coronavirus) and how it affects school operations. As of 5 p.m. on Tuesday, March 24, 2020: In alignment with direction from Tennessee Governor Bill Lee, the closure of Bristol City Schools, Kingsport City Schools, and Sullivan County Schools has been extended through Friday, April 24, 2020. This includes all extra-curricular and athletic activities. Please be aware that assessment of this situation is continuing and any changes regarding additional closures or when and how school will resume will be communicated to you as soon as possible. As a community, we continue to be concerned with the health and well-being of our students, families, and staff. We thank you for your support during this time and wish all of our families the very best of health.

post_text: ATTN Kingsport City Schools Families: Instructional plans for KCS students while we are out for COVID-19 (Coronavirus) has now been released. All of the details are on our website www.k12k.com and also being sent via email. Here are a couple of specific details to make you aware of. For elementary students, learning packets can be picked up at your child's school on Thursday and Friday (March 19 and 20, 2020) of this week between 9 a.m. and 3 p.m. For middle and high school students, online coursework will be provided through your child's 1:1 device using Canvas or Google Classroom. If your student needs a device to access these activities, you can drive through and pick one up tomorrow, March 19, 2020 at Dobyns-Bennett High School between 10 a.m. and 2 p.m. Activities will be provided to allow for any potential extended closure, if necessary. We really to be able to help facilitate ongoing learning of essential information while we are out, and this plan outlines that.

UPDATE (3.18.20): Starting tomorrow, March 19th, we are adding additional bus delivery of free meals throughout our community. We'll now actually be running all of our regular bus routes during both breakfast and lunch loaded up with free meals for any child age 18 or under that would like one.

ATTN Kingsport City Schools Families: We wanted to provide you some important information regarding the feeding program that KCS will be offering during our school closure. FREE BREAKFAST and FREE LUNCH for children 18 and under will be available at most school locations and will be delivered by buses on all days we are closed for COVID-19 (Coronavirus), other than Spring Break, when federal regulations prevent us from doing that. One meal will be given per child, who does not need to be a KCS student. Please visit our website www.k12k.com for additional details.

ICYMIğŸ¤¯ ... Charter Communication announced Friday morning it will offer free Spectrum broadband and Wi-Fi access for 60 days to households with K-12 and/or college students who do not already have a subscription.

The news comes on the heels of the arrival of coronavirus in communities throughout the country, and concerns over transmission of the virus.

A service of up to 100 megabytes per second will be provided.

The offer begins Monday, March 16. Those interested in enrolling are asked to call 844.488.8395. Installation fees will be waived for new student households.

Charter will also open Wi-Fi hot spots across its footprint for public use.

post_text: ATTN: Families and Staff of Bristol, Kingsport City Schools, and Sullivan County Schools... "Like you, we have been monitoring the situation regarding COVID-19 (Coronavirus) and how it is affecting schools and communities across the globe. Locally, we know the recent awareness of a positive diagnosis in our region has our families concerned and wondering how this information will or should impact our schools. In an ongoing collaborative effort, all three school districts in Sullivan County have been continually communicating with each other and local health agencies throughout this situation. This information has guided planning and operational decision-making for all of us, following the guidance of the Sullivan County Health Department, the Tennessee Department of Health, and the Centers for Disease Control. Relying on these experts is allowing us to make informed, coordinated, data-driven decisions based on the most current medical information." Please read the full joint message that can be found on our website at www.k12k.com.

post_text: The Kingsport City Schools Board of Education (BOE) and the Kingsport Board of Mayor and Aldermen will hold a joint work session on Tuesday, March 10, 2020 at 4 p.m. in the Tennessee Room at the KCS Administrative Support Center, 400 Clinchfield Street, third floor, downtown Kingsport. The purpose of this joint work session is to discuss issues related to school district operations and strategic planning for the 2020-2021 school year. All Board meetings are open to the public. post_text: Kingsport City Schools February 2020 BOE Meeting: Two D-B seniors were recognized for being selected as members of the 2024 class of the prestigious Roan Scholars Leadership Program at East Tennessee State University. The honored students are Gavin Bentley and Sally Chikomb. Bentley, the son of Phillip and Amy Bentley, attends D-B EXCEL and has used the field of robotics to learn, lead, and grow other leaders. post_text: Kingsport City Schools February 2020 BOE Meeting: Jackilyn Kenner (4th grade math teacher at Jackson Elementary School), along with students from the Jackson LEGO League team, presented a report on their experience and accomplishments this year. To accomplish the goals of the LEGO League objective, the team worked to find a creative solution to a real-world problem and present that solution to a panel of judges. post_text: @kcs_district January 2020 BOE Meeting: Representatives from D-B EXCEL presented a report to the Board regarding their participation in the 2019 National Christmas Tree Display. DBE was selected as one of the 56 schools across the country to design one-of-a-kind ornaments for the 2019 National Christmas Tree display located on the Ellipse in President's Park in Washington D.C. Each of the 56 schools represented a state, territory, or a district as part of the America Celebrates display. DBE digital arts students utilized #Adobe #Illustrator and #Photoshop to create art that captured the essence of Tennessee landmarks, generating 24 designs that represented the state's three distinct regions. #christmastree #nationalchristmastree #treelighting #christmas #nctl2019 #presidentspark #goparks #nationalparkservice #tennessee #volunteers #tnproud #dobynsbennett #wearedbe #rolltriberoll #studentsuccess #digitalarts #weloveourstudents #breathelife #kingsport #thisiskingsport

post_text: Kingsport City Schools December 2019 BOE Meeting: Board Member Julie Byers recognized members of the Sevier Middle School student newspaper, The Sequoyah Scribe, for winning the 2019 Pacemaker Award! The Sequoyah Scribe was the only middle school in the United States to receive this honor, essentially designating it as the top middle school newspaper in the country. This is the second time the Sequoyah Scribe has won the award, having been named a finalist in 2014, 2017, 2018, and 2019. â­ï¸BRAVO!â­ï¸ #middleschool #studentnewspaper #journalism #journalismstudent #journalismmatters #pacemakeraward #studentsuccess #weloveourstudents #breathelife #kingsport #thisiskingsport
